<p><strong>What can I get from volunteering?</strong></p>
<p>People have different reasons and motivations for volunteering, they may include:</p>
<ul>
<li>to have fun, meet new people and increase social networks</li>
<li>to help my community and/or give something back</li>
<li>to gain experience for employment, like learning new skills such as communication and teamwork</li>
<li>to add to my CV and get a reference</li>
<li>to try something new like working with children or the elderly</li>
<li>to provide structure to my week</li>
<li>to help people going through something I’ve experienced</li>
<li>doing something worthwhile</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Any of these are good reasons to volunteer. If you are clear what your motivation is and what you are hoping to gain or give by volunteering, this will help you to find the right opportunity.</p>
<p><strong>What types of things can I do as a volunteer?</strong></p>
<p>There are loads of different opportunities available – do something you’re already familiar with, or take the plunge and try something completely new – the majority of organisations involving volunteers will value your time and energy above anything else, and will probably offer training to help you in your new role. Sometimes organisations do require specific skills, but if you’re not sure ring them up for more information. If that role is not suitable, there may be something else. Here are a few examples of volunteer roles:</p>
<ul>
<li>Office administration such as updating databases, sending out information</li>
<li>Shop work like sorting stock and displays or serving customers</li>
<li>Use business skills – e.g. develop a marketing strategy, or write a business plan</li>
<li>Become a Trustee – get involved in the running of a charity</li>
<li>Events – help plan and organise fundraising events</li>
<li>IT – show other volunteers and staff how to use computers</li>
<li>Environment – go out in the countryside to clear paths or manage woodland</li>
<li>Sports – coach sports at after school clubs</li>
<li>Visit an elderly person</li>
<li>Drive someone to a hospital appointment</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Where do I start?</strong></p>
<p>Organisations in Buckinghamshire can advertise their volunteer vacancies on VolunteeringBucks.org.uk. So you can search for volunteer opportunities on this site and apply to them directly.</p>
<p><strong> How much time is involved?</strong></p>
<p>The great thing about volunteering is that it’s so varied and flexible you can usually find something to fit in with your life style. It does not have to be the same day or time every week, it could be for a one-off event, a short project or a regular activity. Or you may have some spare moments when you could help from home over the internet. Before you start volunteering have a think about when, how often and how long you want to volunteer for. Then have a look for opportunities which match up to what you want to do.</p>
<p><strong>I have specialist business skills – can I use these in a volunteering role?</strong></p>
<p>There are many organisations in Buckinghamshire that require support from volunteers with business skills in areas including marketing, IT, HR, finance and many others; this assistance is highly valued. You may be on a career break, currently unemployed, retired, or wanting to volunteer in addition to working. If you are interested in using your business skills to benefit the local community, you can find a whole range of roles on <a href="http://volunteeringbucks.org.uk/">VolunteeringBucks.org.uk</a>, and apply directly.</p>
<p><strong>Will I be paid expenses?</strong></p>
<p>Although organisations that involve volunteers are encouraged to pay reasonable expenses to volunteers such as travel and refreshments, there is no obligation for them to do so. &nbsp;If there are any expenses that you feel you need to help you volunteer (such as the bus fare to travel to your place of volunteering), it is advisable to discuss this directly with the organisation. The roles listed on <a href="http://volunteeringbucks.org.uk/">VolunteeringBucks.org.uk</a> state if expenses will be paid.</p>
<p><strong>Will I get paid for my time?</strong></p>
<p>A volunteer is defined as someone who willingly gives their time to a good cause. You will not get paid for your time but usually you will be reimbursed certain expenses from the organisation you volunteer with, so that volunteering does not leave you out of pocket (please refer to the section on expenses above).</p>
<p><strong>Will I receive training?</strong></p>
<p>It is the responsibility of the organisation to ensure that volunteers are able to carry out the role they have applied to do, whatever that may be. Some roles may call for substantial training and support, but others may need less formal training. It really does depend on the type of volunteering you will be doing. You can ask questions about training and induction when you speak to or meet with the organisation.</p>
<p><strong>What does the organisation need from me before I start?</strong></p>
<p>For some voluntary roles, you may just have a chat with someone from the organisation. However depending upon the role some organisations may ask you for some or all of the following:</p>
<ul>
<li>application form</li>
<li>references</li>
<li>interview</li>
<li>criminal record checks – now called DBS checks (especially if volunteers are working with vulnerable people)</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Can I leave if the role isn’t for me?</strong></p>
<p>Yes of course. You are under no obligation to keep volunteering in a role or for an organisation that you are unhappy with. In the first instance, it is always a good idea to speak to someone appropriate about your concerns, for example your supervisor.</p>
<p><strong>Will volunteering affect my benefits?</strong></p>
<p>Volunteering should not affect any state benefits you receive, provided that the only money you get from volunteering is to cover expenses, like travel costs and that you continue to meet the conditions of the benefit you get.</p>
